        "type": "text",
        "text": "Now I have all six. Here's the batch triage:\n\n| # | Counterparty | Verdict | Top Issues | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ACME Tooling Solutions | **GREEN** | None | Sign without legal review |\n| 2 | BetaCorp Logistics | **YELLOW** | Long survival (7yr post-term), broad CI definition, no-publicity clause | Legal review & redline |\n| 3 | Cypress Systems | **RED** | Perpetual term, no residuals carve-out, no-reverse-engineering clause, California jurisdiction | Escalate to GC |\n| 4 | Delphi Components | **GREEN** | None | Sign without legal review |\n| 5 | Emberlake Holdings | **YELLOW** | Overbroad CI definition, limited carve-outs, non-solicitation clause (12mo) | Legal review & redline |\n| 6 | Folium Research Institute | **GREEN** | None | Sign without legal review |\n\n---\n\n## Detail on YELLOW & RED items:\n\n**BetaCorp Logistics (YELLOW):**\n- **Survival**: 5-year operative + 7-year post-term = 12 years total. Playbook threshold is 7 years combined. Push to 2-year operative + 3-year survival.\n- **CI definition** (Clause 1): \"all information disclosed by Discloser to Recipient, in any form, in connection with the Purpose, whether or not marked or identified as confidential.\" This is too broad — anything said captures as CI. Redline to require marking or identification at time of disclosure (see ACME's language as model).\n- **No-publicity clause** (Clause 5): Restricts \"disclosure to any third party the existence or substance of any discussions\" without consent. This is broader than standard. Redline to permit disclosure to legal advisers and where required by law, and narrow to discussions only (not the existence of the relationship post-deal).\n- **Missing residuals carve-out**: Not fatal but worth adding for consistency with market standard.\n\n**Cypress Systems (RED):**\n- **Perpetual term** (Clause 3): \"This Agreement is perpetual and continues in force indefinitely.\" No fixed expiry is not acceptable — it creates indefinite liability exposure decades later. This is a disqualifying issue.\n- **No residuals carve-out** (Clause 4): \"There is no carve-out for residual information retained in the unaided memory of personnel.\" Confidentiality should not restrict use of information retained in personnel's heads; this is overreach.\n- **No reverse-engineering carve-out** (Clause 5): Restricts reverse engineering of software/algorithms. Fine for SaaS delivery, but this is being imposed on us as the buyer of a SaaS platform — we should be free to reverse-engineer for our own product development to the extent permitted by law. This signals over-protective counterparty mindset.\n- **California jurisdiction**: Not RED on its own, but combined with other issues, enforcement in California courts would be costly for us. Combined with perpetual term, this is a non-starter.\n\nDo not sign Cypress without GC involvement and likely substantial redline work. The perpetual term alone disqualifies it.\n\n**Emberlake Holdings (YELLOW):**\n- **CI definition** (Clause 1): \"including information that is publicly available but compiled, organised, or contextualised by the disclosing party.\" This is overbroad — it treats any structured compilation of public data as Confidential Information. Narrow to \"information that the disclosing party identifies in writing as confidential\" (Folium's language is better).\n- **Limited carve-outs** (Clause 3): Only \"contemporaneous written records\" carve-out. Missing standard exceptions for independent development, third-party receipt without restriction, compelled disclosure. Redline to add all four.\n- **Non-solicitation** (Clause 5): 12-month post-term restriction on solicitation of employees \"with whom it had contact.\" This is a beyond-confidentiality clause that doesn't belong in an NDA. Redline to remove it; if Emberlake pushes back, limit to 6 months and persons \"directly involved in the discussions\" only.\n- **No-publicity clause** (Clause 6): Mutual prohibition on public statements without consent. Standard; keep as is.\n\n---\n\n**Summary for your decision:**\n\n- **Sign immediately** (Greens): ACME, Delphi, Folium. No legal resource required.\n- **Send to legal for redline** (Yellows): BetaCorp, Emberlake. Both are closeable with one round of edits; flag to your relationship leads that survival and non-solicitation terms are points of push.\n- **Escalate to GC** (Red): Cypress. Perpetual term is disqualifying. Do not negotiate around it unless GC decides this counterparty is strategically critical enough to override the standard."
      }
