        "type": "text",
        "text": "| **TO:** legal@cypressystems.com |\n| **FROM:** [Your Legal Counsel] |\n| **RE:** Cypress Systems NDA – proposed amendments |\n\n---\n\nThank you for sending your NDA. We're keen to move forward and appreciate the opportunity to discuss your cloud platform. We've reviewed the agreement and identified three issues we'll need to address before we can execute:\n\n**1. Term and Survival (Clause 3)**\n\nYour agreement provides for perpetual obligations with no termination date. We're unable to accept indefinite confidentiality undertakings — they create unmanageable long-tail liability and complicate our records management. We propose:\n\n- Operative term: 2 years from signature\n- Survival: 3 years from disclosure of each item\n\nThis is market-standard for commercial evaluations and reflects the typical lifecycle of a product assessment.\n\n**2. Residual Information (Clause 4)**\n\nYour current language excludes any carve-out for information retained in personnel's unaided memory. We need to add a residuals exception — it's standard across our vendor NDAs and reflects the practical reality that employees retain general knowledge from discussions. Proposed language:\n\n> \"Receiving Party shall not be in breach by virtue of any use of residual information retained in the unaided memory of its personnel, provided such personnel did not intentionally retain such information in violation of this Agreement.\"\n\n**3. Reverse-Engineering Restriction (Clause 5)**\n\nYour agreement restricts reverse engineering of software. While we understand the concern, this restriction is unusually broad for an evaluation NDA. We propose narrowing it to: \"Receiving Party shall not reverse-engineer Confidential Information solely for the purpose of developing a competing product or service.\" This preserves your legitimate concerns without restricting lawful analysis for operational purposes.\n\nI've attached a marked-up version reflecting these changes. Happy to discuss — let me know what works for your side.\n\nBest regards,\n\n[Your Name]  \n[Your Title]\n\n---\n\n**Tone note:** This is firm but collaborative. It names the three must-haves (perpetual term, residuals, reverse-eng) without relitigating every other point. It offers specific redline language so they know exactly what you need, not a laundry list of options. Keep it short — legal teams respect brevity."
